---
import ToolLayout from '../../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';
import StrengthStandardsCalculator from '../../components/calculators/StrengthStandardsCalculator.astro';
---

<ToolLayout
  title="Strength Standards Calculator"
  description="Calculate realistic strength standards and goals based on your age and experience level. Specifically designed for men over 40 to ensure safe and effective progress."
>
  <div class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none mb-8">
    <h2>Understanding Strength Standards After 40</h2>
    <p>
      Strength standards for men over 40 need to be viewed differently than those for younger lifters. While building and 
      maintaining strength is absolutely achievable, factors like recovery capacity, joint health, and hormonal changes 
      need to be considered.
    </p>
    
    <div class="my-6">
      <h3>Key Factors Influencing Strength After 40</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Recovery Capacity:</strong> Generally requires more time between heavy training sessions</li>
        <li><strong>Joint Health:</strong> May require modifications to standard lifting techniques</li>
        <li><strong>Hormonal Changes:</strong> Can affect strength gains and recovery</li>
        <li><strong>Training History:</strong> Previous experience greatly influences potential</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <StrengthStandardsCalculator />

  <div class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none mt-8">
    <div class="my-6 p-4 bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-lg">
      <h3 class="mt-0">How to Use These Standards</h3>
      
      <h4>Interpreting Your Results</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Beginner:</strong> Achievable within first year of consistent training</li>
        <li><strong>Intermediate:</strong> Typically requires 1-3 years of focused training</li>
        <li><strong>Advanced:</strong> Representative of several years of dedicated training</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Important Considerations</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Standards are adjusted for age-related factors</li>
        <li>Focus on steady, sustainable progress</li>
        <li>Form and safety should always come first</li>
        <li>Individual results may vary based on numerous factors</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Training Guidelines for Strength Development</h2>

    <h3>Exercise Selection Principles</h3>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      <div>
        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Compound Movements</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Bench Press variations</li>
          <li>Squat variations</li>
          <li>Deadlift variations</li>
          <li>Overhead Press</li>
          <li>Row variations</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Joint-Friendly Alternatives</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Floor Press (shoulder-friendly)</li>
          <li>Box Squats (knee-friendly)</li>
          <li>Trap Bar Deadlift (lower back-friendly)</li>
          <li>Landmine Press (shoulder-friendly)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Programming Guidelines</h3>
    <div class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 p-4 rounded-lg">
      <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Sample Training Split</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Day 1: Upper Body Push (Bench Focus)</li>
        <li>Day 2: Lower Body (Squat Focus)</li>
        <li>Day 3: Rest/Recovery</li>
        <li>Day 4: Upper Body Pull</li>
        <li>Day 5: Lower Body (Deadlift Focus)</li>
        <li>Day 6-7: Rest/Recovery</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Volume and Intensity Guidelines</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Main Lifts:</strong> 3-5 sets of 3-8 reps</li>
      <li><strong>Accessory Work:</strong> 2-3 sets of 8-15 reps</li>
      <li><strong>Weekly Frequency:</strong> 1-2 times per lift</li>
      <li><strong>Intensity:</strong> 65-85% of 1RM for main work</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-900 p-4 rounded-lg mt-6">
      <h3 class="text-blue-900 dark:text-blue-100 mt-0">Progress Tracking Tips</h3>
      <ul class="text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-200">
        <li>Keep a detailed training log</li>
        <li>Track both weight and reps</li>
        <li>Note joint comfort and recovery quality</li>
        <li>Adjust volume based on recovery</li>
        <li>Progress in small increments (2.5-5 lbs)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6">
      <h3>Recovery and Injury Prevention</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Warm-up:</strong> Spend extra time on mobility and activation</li>
        <li><strong>Form:</strong> Regular video analysis of main lifts</li>
        <li><strong>Deload:</strong> Every 4-6 weeks based on fatigue</li>
        <li><strong>Recovery Methods:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Adequate sleep (7-9 hours)</li>
            <li>Proper nutrition</li>
            <li>Stress management</li>
            <li>Active recovery (walking, swimming)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</ToolLayout>
